{"person":{"id":"HD2332","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"X00740","mother_id":"HD2283"},"tags":["civil_war","harvard_graduate","killed_in_action","military"],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1831,"month":6,"city":"Lenox","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1862,"month":9,"day":29,"city":"Keedysville","county":"Washington County","state":"Maryland","country":"United States"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00765","children_ids":["HD2365","HD2366","HD2367"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1857,"date_month":7,"date_day":15,"location_city":"Hanover","location_state":"Germany"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["military"],"notable_blurb":"Union major mortally wounded at Antietam","primary_url":"https://antietam.aotw.org/officers.php?officer_id=6764","primary_url_label":"Antietam on the Web"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Maj. William Dwight Sedgwick","first_name":"William","last_name":"Sedgwick","middle_name":"Dwight","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780719050/166303887_2c81509b-6b28-41a6-8368-bac7eaf79bc8_bm2lgh.jpg","title":"Major"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[{"war":"American Civil War","active_in_war":true,"rank":"Major","unit":"2nd Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry; staff of Gen. John Sedgwick","notes":"Mortally wounded at Antietam, September 1862.","war_id":"WAR006"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"military","header":"He fell rallying a broken regiment at Antietam","body":"As assistant adjutant general to General John Sedgwick, William Dwight Sedgwick rode into the West Woods slaughter on September 17, 1862, where the division lost two thousand men in half an hour. When the line broke he spurred to the disordered 34th New York to rally it and was shot through the back, toppling from his horse.","number":1},{"category":"character","header":"Eight hours alone with no friend near","body":"Left paralyzed and abandoned as the New Yorkers fled, Sedgwick lay among bursting shells for eight hours. He drew out his pocket diary and wrote that he had not uttered a groan, lying alone in the hot sun with no friend near.","number":2},{"category":"family","header":"His mother reached him before the end","body":"From the field hospital at Keedysville he wrote twice to his mother, making light of his wound so she need not travel to him. She and his sister Grace came regardless and were beside him when he died on September 29.","number":3},{"category":"family","header":"His wife learned of his death abroad","body":"His wife Louisa had already sailed for Germany and could not be recalled; she learned she was a widow only after landing in Europe. He left three daughters, the youngest born two months after he left for the front and never once seen by her father.","number":4},{"category":"character","header":"Comrades remembered a merry, fearless man","body":"The afternoon before the battle he rode to his old regiment and talked for two hours, leaving 'merry and jolly,' Captain Robert Gould Shaw recalled. General Oliver Howard later wrote that no one's conduct was as cool and brave, and that no soldier deserved higher commendation.","number":5}],"burial":{"cemetery_name":"Stockbridge Cemetery","city":"Stockbridge","county":"Berkshire County","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"slug":"william-sedgwick-1831"},"neighborhood":{"focus":{"id":"HD2332","slug":"william-sedgwick-1831","n":"Maj. William Dwight Sedgwick","by":1831,"dy":1862,"sx":"m","hd":true,"td":false,"ee":false,"g":8},